                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d287">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">868.51/1272: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in France (<persName type="to">Edge</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-10-21T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 21, 1932—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>379. Please repeat your 608, October 20, 3 p.m., to Embassies at London and
                    Rome.</p>
                <p>Department is again taking matter up through London and Athens. The last
                    paragraph of your telegram is particularly disturbing. Department does not
                    understand the reported British position in view of the fact that the American
                    Government has advised Greece that it expects the November 10th payment to be
                    made. The Treasury has not consented to any negotiations with respect to the
                    postponement of this payment. Please communicate these facts to the appropriate
                    French authorities.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
